ian)|Tony Banks]] - ''[[The Shout]]'', starring [[Alan Bates]], [[Susannah York]] and [[John Hurt]].\n*[[Roy Budd]] - ''[[The Wild Geese]]''.\n*[[Ron Goodwin]] - ''[[Force 10 from Navarone (film)|Force 10 from Navarone]]'' directed by [[Guy Hamilton]], starring [[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]] and [[Edward Fox (actor)|Edward Fox]].\n*[[Ed Welch]] - ''[[The Thirty Nine Steps (1978 film)|The Thirty Nine Steps]]'', starring [[Robert Powell]].\n\n==Births==\n*[[1 January]] - [[Tarik O'Regan]], composer\n*[[3 January]] - [[Luke Manning]], co-founder of Mostar Records\n*[[15 January]] - [[Sandi Lee Hughes]], singer ([[allSTARS*]])\n*[[13 February]] - [[Hamish Glencross]], Scottish guitarist\n*[[14 February]] - [[Ryan Griffiths (guitarist)|Ryan Griffiths]] ([[The Vines (band)|The Vines]])\n*[[22 February]] - [[Jenny Frost]], singer ([[Atomic Kitten]])\n*[[6 April]] - [[Myleene Klass]], singer ([[Hear'Say]]), radio and TV presenter\n*[[7 April]] - [[Duncan James]], singer ([[Blue (boy band)|Blue]])\n*[[9 April]] - [[Rachel Stevens]], singer ([[S Club 7]])\n*[[28 April]] - [[Lauren Laverne]], singer, radio DJ and TV presenter\n*[[4 May]] - [[Matthew Rose (bass)|Matthew Rose]], bass\n*[[22 May]] - [[Jordan (model)|Jordan]], model and would-be singer\n*[[6 June]] - [[Sophie Solomon]], violinist\n*[[27 June]] - [[Lolly (singer)|Lolly]], singer\n*[[4 July]] - [[Stephen McNally (musician)|Stephen McNally]], English singer-songwriter ([[BBMak]])\n*[[15 September]] - [[David Sneddon]], singer-songwriter\n*[[9 October]] - [[Nicky Byrne]], Irish singer ([[Westlife]])\n*[[27 November]] - [[Mike Skinner (musician)|Mike Skinner]], rapper, musician and record producer\n*[[18 December]] - [[Lindsay Armaou]], Greek-born Irish-based singer ([[B*Witched]])\n\n==Deaths==\n*[[11 January]] - [[William John Edwards]], Cerdd Dant singer (b. 1898)\n*[[15 January]] - [[Jack Jackson (British radio)|Jack Jackson]], trumpeter, bandleader and radio disc jockey (b. 1906)\n*[[24 February]] - [[Mrs Mills]], pianist (b. 1918)\n*[[9 March]] - [[L. Radley Flynn]], singer and actor (b. 1902)\n*[[12 March]] - [[Tolchard Evans]], songwriter, composer, pianist and bandleader (b. 1901)\n*[[3 April]] - [[Ray Noble (musician)|Ray Noble]], composer and bandleader (b. 1903)\n*[[21 April]] - [[Sandy Denny]], singer ([[Fairport Convention]]) (b. 1947) (cerebral haemorrhage)\n*[[14 August]] - [[Victor Silvester]], dance band leader (b. 1900)\n*[[7 September]]\n**<!--September 7-->[[Keith Moon]], drummer for [[The Who]] (b. 1946) ([[Clomethiazole]] overdose)\n**<!--September 7-->[[Charles Williams (composer)|Charles Williams]], composer (b. 1893)\n*[[15 September]] - [[Edmund Crispin|Robert Bruce Montgomery]], composer (b. 1921)\n*[[13 November]] - [[W. S. Gwynn Williams]], musician and composer (b. 1896)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1978 in British radio]]\n* [[1978 in British television]]\n* [[1978 in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of British films of 1978]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Music of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:British music by year]]\n[[Category:1978 in British music]]\n", "text_old": "{{1970s in music (UK)}}\n{{YYYY music|1978}}\n{{Year nav topic5|1978|British music}}\n\nThis is a summary of [[1978 in music]] in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Events==\n*[[14 January]] - The [[Sex Pistols]] played their final show (until a reunion in 1996).\n*[[24 January]] - [[Wings (band)|Wings]]' \"[[Mull of Kintyre (song)|Mull of Kintyre]]\" made No.1 for its ninth (and final) week - becoming the biggest-selling single in UK history at that point.\n*[[25 January]] - [[Electric Light Orchestra]] kicked off their ''[[Out of the Blue (Electric Light Orchestra album)|Out of the Blue]]'' world tour in [[Honolulu]], Hawaii.\n*[[11 March]] - [[Kate Bush]] became the first female solo artist to reach number one in the UK charts with a self-written song (\"[[Wuthering Heights (song)|Wuthering Heights]]\").\n*[[30 April]] - [[The Clash]], [[Tom Robinson Band]], [[Steel Pulse]], [[X-Ray Spex]], [[the Ruts]], [[Misty in Roots]] and [[Generation X (band)|Generation X]] all play live in [[Victoria Park, London|Victoria Park]], Hackney at the [[Anti-Nazi League]]/[[Rock Against Racism]] festival, following a march from [[Trafalgar Square]].\n*[[25 May]] - [[The Who]] played their last show with [[Keith Moon]].\n*[[30 July]] \u2013 [[Thin Lizzy]] officially announced that [[Gary Moore]] had replaced [[Brian Robertson (guitarist)|Brian Robertson]] on guitar.\n*[[18 August]] - [[The Who]] released their eighth studio ''[[Who Are You]]''. It is The Who's last album with [[Keith Moon]] as the drummer; Moon died twenty days after the release of this album.\n*[[September]] - Second anti-racism event staged in [[Brockwell Park]], South London, featuring [[Elvis Costello]], [[Stiff Little Fingers]] & [[Aswad]], with 150,000 attending.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n*[[27 November]] - [[Def Leppard]]'s permanent drummer [[Rick Allen (drummer)|Rick Allen]] joined the band at the age of 15.\n*[[The Bee Gees]]' [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|''Saturday Night Fever'']] became the biggest-selling album of all time (until overtaken in 1983).\n*First [[BBC Young Musician]] of the Year competition for classical players won by trombonist [[Michael Hext]].\n*Operatic contralto [[Helen Watts]] is appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]].\n*[[Multitone Records]] is founded by Pranil Gohil and specializing in bhangra style music.\n\n== Charts ==\n\n=== Number one singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Date!!Song!!Artist\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | 7 January|| rowspan=4| \"[[Mull of Kintyre (song)|Mull of Kintyre]]\" / \"[[Girls' School (song)|Girls' School]]\"|| rowspan=4| [[Wings (band)|Wings]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | 14 January \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | 21 January\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | 28 January\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | 4 February||\"[[Uptown 